<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-601-118  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 601 118.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  August 17 1989 v15 n17 p24(2).andM;ne</JOURNAL><TITLE>On-line databases a thriving market.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The market for on-line databases continues to expand and evolve.andO;No longer the domain of librarians, information services are nowutilized in a wide range of professional activities such as thepractice of law, medicine and science.andP;  The use of informationstorage and retrieval systems by home users with microcomputers isanother major market that is now developing.andP;  This wide usagestimulates a marketing strategy revolving around user friendlyapplications and ease of access.andP;  The basic distinction in theinformation industry is between database producers and databasevendors.andP;  They may provide such traditional bibliographicdatabases as MEDLINE, for information on medical literature andERIC, which is education-related.andP;  Numeric databases are usedprimarily to provide stock quotations and interest rates.andP;  CD-ROMtechnology and home use are significant trends for future industrygrowth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   MEDLINE (Data base) (marketing)ERIC (Data base) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Information ServicesData BasesInformation Storage and RetrievalTrendsMarket PenetrationBibliographic Data Bases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>